Smart enumerations, also known as value objects, are a fundamental concept in Domain-Driven Design (DDD). They are immutable objects that represent a set of distinct values that have a specific meaning within a particular context.

Here's an example of how to implement a smart enumeration in C#:

```csharp
public class OrderStatus
{
    public static readonly OrderStatus Pending = new OrderStatus("Pending");
    public static readonly OrderStatus Shipped = new OrderStatus("Shipped");
    public static readonly OrderStatus Delivered = new OrderStatus("Delivered");

    private readonly string _name;

    private OrderStatus(string name)
    {
        _name = name;
    }

    public override string ToString()
    {
        return _name;
    }

    public static OrderStatus FromString(string name)
    {
        return name switch
        {
            "Pending" => Pending,
            "Shipped" => Shipped,
            "Delivered" => Delivered,
            _ => throw new ArgumentException("Invalid order status", nameof(name)),
        };
    }

    public static implicit operator string(OrderStatus status)
    {
        return status.ToString();
    }

    public static implicit operator OrderStatus(string status)
    {
        return FromString(status);
    }
}
``

